 to minor acts of everyday resistance against injustice, to attempts to restore security and stability once afforded by the Soviet state.Painting a complex portrait, For Putin and for Sharia challenges the official dichotomy of Muslims as supporting either the political underground or state authorities. Kaliszewska deconstructs the Salafi/Sufi division between the so-called reformists and traditional Islam that has perpetuated in writing about the post-Soviet space. Included is the self-reflection of a researcher in a conflict zone, how the experience can shift understanding of the ways people think and live.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aIslam and statezRussia (Federation)zDagestan. 0aIslamzRussia (Federation)zDagestan. 0aMuslimszRussia (Federation)zDagestan. 4aETHNOLOGY. 4aIslamic Religion & Studies. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aterrorism in dagestan, islam in the post-Soviet area, sharia in twenty first century dagestan, jihad in the north caucasus.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075183340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150176765440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501767654423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501767654/original  a978-3-11-075183-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK